## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8:

| Line | Pattern | Issue |
|------|---------|-------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `SYSLIB0006` / throws at runtime |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup on forced stop | Never fires — exception type gone |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `SYSLIB0006` / throws at runtime |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (replaces ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop condition
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
            _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — cooperative signal instead of forcible thread tear-down.

2. **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`** — the `when` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones.

3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — no longer needed; the loop naturally checks `token.IsCancellationRequested` and continues or exits.

4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(2s)`** — actually waits for the thread instead of hoping it finishes during a blind sleep.

5. **Token passed to `GetNextItem`** — critical! If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it must accept the token so it can unblock when cancelled.

## Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls

If `GetNextItem` blocks without checking the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it and your `Stop()` will hang. Fix the blocking call:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely
private object GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // no way to interrupt except Thread.Abort
}

// After (.NET 8) — cancellation-aware
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}
```

If the blocking call is a `Thread.Sleep`:
```csharp
// Before:  Thread.Sleep(5000);
// After:   token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);  // wakes immediately on cancel
```

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers/callbacks. Always `Dispose()`. |
| Forgetting to pass token through the call chain | Cancellation stalls at the first method that ignores it. |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations. |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` in inner methods | Let it propagate — only handle it at the top-level loop. |
